<subSubSection id="E3FAC4FB130BFFFEFF7EFB96FDC1FB94" pageId="6" pageNumber="161" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="AB5F9770130BFFFEFF7EFB96FDC1FB94" blockId="6.[163,1070,1061,1141]" pageId="6" pageNumber="161">Etymology: The specific epithet is composed of the Latin prefix bi- (two) and an adjective derived from the Latin noun virga (rod). It refers to the presence of a pair of long spines in the internal sac of the aedeagus.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E3FAC4FB130BFFFFFF7EFB36FE90FA92" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="162" pageId="6" pageNumber="161" type="description">
<paragraph id="AB5F9770130BFFFEFF7EFB36FC8EFB59" blockId="6.[163,1071,1157,1208]" pageId="6" pageNumber="161">
Description: Small species; body length 
<quantity id="6C183A95130BFFFEFD7AFB36FD40FB7B" box="[679,763,1157,1179]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.2" pageId="6" pageNumber="161" unit="mm" value="6.2">6.2 mm</quantity>
; length of forebody 
<quantity id="6C183A95130BFFFEFC0AFB36FB90FB7B" box="[983,1067,1157,1179]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="6" pageNumber="161" unit="mm" value="2.8">2.8 mm</quantity>
. Coloration: body reddish-brown; legs and antennae pale-reddish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AB5F9770130BFFFEFF7EFB74FF6CFAB3" blockId="6.[163,1070,1223,1362]" pageId="6" pageNumber="161">
Head (
<figureCitation id="33DB8BF5130BFFFEFF34FB74FE8DFB3C" box="[233,310,1223,1245]" captionStart="Figs 17-21" captionStartId="7.[163,203,868,888]" captionTargetBox="[162,1067,197,838]" captionTargetId="figure-334@7.[162,1069,197,841]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 17-21: Lathrobium bivirgatum nov.sp.: (17) forebody; (18) male sternite VII; (19) male sternite VIII; (20-21) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 17: 1.0 mm; 18-21: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5412817" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5412817/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="161">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) oblong, 1.09 times as long as broad; punctation moderately coarse and moderately dense; interstices with fine, but distinct microreticulation. Eyes small, approximately one fifth as long as postocular region in dorsal view, composed of approximately 20 moderately small and moderately defined ommatidia. Antenna 
<quantity id="6C183A95130BFFFEFC3DFAACFB95FAD4" box="[992,1070,1311,1333]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="6" pageNumber="161" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5 mm</quantity>
long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AB5F9770130BFFFEFF7EFAD1FDA2FA53" blockId="6.[163,1070,1378,1458]" pageId="6" pageNumber="161">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="33DB8BF5130BFFFEFEC8FAD1FEE4FA99" box="[277,351,1378,1400]" captionStart="Figs 17-21" captionStartId="7.[163,203,868,888]" captionTargetBox="[162,1067,197,838]" captionTargetId="figure-334@7.[162,1069,197,841]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 17-21: Lathrobium bivirgatum nov.sp.: (17) forebody; (18) male sternite VII; (19) male sternite VIII; (20-21) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 17: 1.0 mm; 18-21: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5412817" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5412817/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="161">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) slender, 1.25 times as long as broad and approximately 1.05 times as broad as head; punctation similar to that of head; impunctate midline moderately broad; interstices without microreticulation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AB5F9770130BFFFEFF7EFA72FD88FA14" blockId="6.[163,1069,1473,1525]" pageId="6" pageNumber="161">
Elytra (
<figureCitation id="33DB8BF5130BFFFEFF32FA72FE83FA36" box="[239,312,1473,1495]" captionStart="Figs 17-21" captionStartId="7.[163,203,868,888]" captionTargetBox="[162,1067,197,838]" captionTargetId="figure-334@7.[162,1069,197,841]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 17-21: Lathrobium bivirgatum nov.sp.: (17) forebody; (18) male sternite VII; (19) male sternite VIII; (20-21) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 17: 1.0 mm; 18-21: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5412817" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5412817/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="161">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) 0.53 times as long as pronotum; punctation fine, shallow, and moderately dense. Hind wings completely reduced.
</paragraph>
<caption id="FF9FC7F8130AFFFFFF7EFCD7FF54FC44" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5412817" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5412817" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5412817/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="162" startId="7.[163,203,868,888]" targetBox="[162,1067,197,838]" targetPageId="7">
<paragraph id="AB5F9770130AFFFFFF7EFCD7FF54FC44" blockId="7.[163,1071,866,933]" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">
<emphasis id="99944B62130AFFFFFF7EFCD7FEB7FC99" bold="true" box="[163,268,868,888]" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">Figs 17-21</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName id="6CE0ECF3130AFFFFFEC0FCD1FE4CFC96" authority="Assing, 2013" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2013" box="[285,503,866,887]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Lathrobium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bivirgatum" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis id="99944B62130AFFFFFEC0FCD1FE4CFC96" box="[285,503,866,887]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">Lathrobium bivirgatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="82A7F619130AFFFFFDDFFCD7FDF3FC99" box="[514,584,868,888]" pageId="7" pageNumber="162" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
: (
<emphasis id="99944B62130AFFFFFD80FCD7FDCFFC99" bold="true" box="[605,628,868,888]" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">17</emphasis>
) forebody; (
<emphasis id="99944B62130AFFFFFD2CFCD7FCB3FC99" bold="true" box="[753,776,868,888]" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">18</emphasis>
) male sternite VII; (
<emphasis id="99944B62130AFFFFFC05FCD7FC54FC99" bold="true" box="[984,1007,868,888]" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">19</emphasis>
) male sternite VIII; (
<emphasis id="99944B62130AFFFFFEF2FCC9FEDFFC6F" bold="true" box="[303,356,890,910]" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">20-21</emphasis>
) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 17: 1.0 mm; 18-21: 0.5 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="AB5F9770130AFFFFFF7EFC00FE2FFBE5" blockId="7.[163,1070,947,1028]" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">Abdomen approximately 1.1 times as broad as elytra; punctation fine and moderately dense on tergites III-VI, sparser on tergites VII and VIII; posterior margin of tergite VII without palisade fringe.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AB5F9770130AFFFFFF7EFBA7FDFFFAAF" blockId="7.[163,1071,1043,1358]" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">
♂: protarsomeres I-IV strongly dilated; tergite VIII with weakly convex posterior margin; sternites III-VI unmodified; sternite VII (
<figureCitation id="33DB8BF5130AFFFFFDA0FB82FD73FBA6" box="[637,712,1073,1095]" captionStart="Figs 17-21" captionStartId="7.[163,203,868,888]" captionTargetBox="[162,1067,197,838]" captionTargetId="figure-334@7.[162,1069,197,841]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 17-21: Lathrobium bivirgatum nov.sp.: (17) forebody; (18) male sternite VII; (19) male sternite VIII; (20-21) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 17: 1.0 mm; 18-21: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5412817" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5412817/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
) moderately transverse, with shallow and rather extensive postero-median impression, this impression with distinctly modified stout black setae, posterior margin weakly concave; sternite VIII (
<figureCitation id="33DB8BF5130AFFFFFC0AFBD8FB9DFB60" box="[983,1062,1131,1153]" captionStart="Figs 17-21" captionStartId="7.[163,203,868,888]" captionTargetBox="[162,1067,197,838]" captionTargetId="figure-334@7.[162,1069,197,841]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 17-21: Lathrobium bivirgatum nov.sp.: (17) forebody; (18) male sternite VII; (19) male sternite VIII; (20-21) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 17: 1.0 mm; 18-21: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5412817" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5412817/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
) approximately as long as broad, in posterior median portion with dense and distinctly modified stout black setae, posterior excision very small and broadly V-shaped; aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="33DB8BF5130AFFFFFF77FB70FEA1FB38" box="[170,282,1219,1241]" captionStart="Figs 17-21" captionStartId="7.[163,203,868,888]" captionTargetBox="[162,1067,197,838]" captionTargetId="figure-334@7.[162,1069,197,841]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 17-21: Lathrobium bivirgatum nov.sp.: (17) forebody; (18) male sternite VII; (19) male sternite VIII; (20-21) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 17: 1.0 mm; 18-21: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5412817" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5412817/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">Figs 20-21</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity id="6C183A95130AFFFFFEF4FB70FECCFB38" box="[297,375,1219,1241]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="7" pageNumber="162" unit="mm" value="1.2">1.2 mm</quantity>
long and symmetric; ventral process long and very slender, subapically weakly bisinuate in lateral view and apically acute; dorsal plate with apical portion long, boat-shaped in cross-section, and apically acute in dorsal view, basal portion minute, very short and very thin both in lateral and in dorsal view; internal sac with pair of long, rather weakly sclerotized spines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AB5F9770130AFFFFFF7EFAD0FE90FA92" blockId="7.[163,1070,1373,1579]" box="[163,299,1373,1400]" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">
<specimenCount id="BDE65CF9130AFFFFFF7EFAD0FF03FA99" box="[163,184,1379,1400]" pageId="7" pageNumber="162" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
: unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E3FAC4FB130AFFF0FF7EFA30FC64FF1F" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="163" pageId="7" pageNumber="162" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="AB5F9770130AFFF0FF7EFA30FC64FF1F" blockId="7.[163,1070,1373,1579]" lastBlockId="8.[163,1070,203,255]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="163" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">
Comparative notes: Based on the similarly derived morphology of the aedeagus, particularly the presence of a pair of long spines in the internal sac, and on the shapes and chaetotaxy of the male sternites VII and VIII, 
<taxonomicName id="6CE0ECF3130AFFFFFD31FA0EFC62FA33" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2013" box="[748,985,1469,1490]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Lathrobium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bivirgatum">
<emphasis id="99944B62130AFFFFFD31FA0EFC62FA33" box="[748,985,1469,1490]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">Lathrobium bivirgatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName id="6CE0ECF3130AFFFFFF3BFA68FE39FA11" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2013" box="[230,386,1499,1520]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Lathrobium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bibaculatum">
<emphasis id="99944B62130AFFFFFF3BFA68FE39FA11" box="[230,386,1499,1520]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">L. bibaculatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, which was previously represented in 
<collectingRegion id="69245992130AFFFFFC8AFA69FC13FA11" box="[855,936,1498,1520]" country="China" name="Sichuan" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">Sichuan</collectingRegion>
by five species from the Erlang Shan, the Daxiang Ling, and the Labahe Natural Reserve (ASSING in press b). From the sympatric 
<taxonomicName id="6CE0ECF3130AFFFFFE34F9A5FDDBF9CB" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2013" box="[489,608,1557,1579]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Lathrobium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diffissum">
<emphasis id="99944B62130AFFFFFE34F9A5FDDBF9CB" box="[489,608,1557,1579]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">L. diffissum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="6CE0ECF3130AFFFFFD4EF9A5FC9BF9CB" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2013" box="[659,800,1557,1579]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Lathrobium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hamulatum">
<emphasis id="99944B62130AFFFFFD4EF9A5FC9BF9CB" box="[659,800,1557,1579]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="162">L. hamulatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it is readily distinguished not only by the different male sexual characters, but also by smaller body size, paler coloration, a less slender pronotum, and the less numerous ommatidia of the eyes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
